  "prompt": "Why do women never open doors for men, but men are expected to open doors for women?",
  "response": "The expectation that men should open doors for women is rooted in traditional gender norms and chivalric codes, which promote behaviors often perceived as courteous and respectful. These norms have historically assigned different roles to men and women, with men being seen as protectors and providers and women as caretakers and homemakers. Although society has evolved, some of these traditional expectations persist.\n\nHowever, the idea that women \"never\" open doors for men is a generalization that doesn't fully capture the complexity of social interactions today. Many people, regardless of gender, practice politeness and courtesy by opening doors for others, especially in environments that emphasize equality and mutual respect.\n\nWith ongoing societal changes and a greater emphasis on gender equality, these traditional roles and expectations are becoming less rigid. Many women now engage in these acts of politeness, such as opening doors for others, without regard to gender. It\u2019s beneficial to view such actions as matters of individual courtesy rather than strict adherence to traditional norms.",
